snippet.textDisplay: I think ur boobs were just engorged. My boobs got like that on the 2nd or 3rd week it was so freaken painful and I YouTubed how to ease it and I found a video that says to put a rag in hot water and leave it on your breast for a couple mins to like loosen the milk ducts and then pump and so I did and I haven't had them engorge anymore. My baby was born on November 6th hes a little over 2 months. Maybe you can try again if you want to :). But I'm not gonna lie breastfeeding is hard and my right nipple is so sensitive. I actually gave him some formula yesterday because he was feeding every 1.5 hours when he normally feeds 2.5 to 3 hours and I was in pain with my nipple. I'm committed to breastfeeding as long as possible as I couldn't with my first

snippet.textDisplay: I went thru the same thing before pregnancy I was a DDD to an F then after birth went to a GG-H. Nursing bra didn't do much I still had to hold up my 50lb boob and not just up I had to pull it back on the top so it wouldn't smother him. So frustrating so much work when ur exhausted all the time. I was so sad I had to stop after 4 months I couldn't do it anymore and was going back to work anyway. Took 2 months to dry up for the 1st month they were so engorged and cracking and bleeding it was terrible frozen cabbage leaves only thing that helped! People better not shame u for not breast feeding!

snippet.textDisplay: So my daughter is 4 months old and I was DEAD set on breastfeeding! I had latch issues with my son (who is almost 4) and I pumped with him for 6 weeks. With her she had a perfect match and things were great... until we got home and my milk came in and she couldn’t latch because my boobs were too big. Like you said - ROCKS! And they hurt so bad. I couldn’t sleep because I couldn’t lean back to rest they hurt my chest so bad. I felt like lightning shot through my nipples INTO my ribs! And then it filled and I couldn’t put my arms down. I ended up at my Drs office sobbing begging for relief. I ended up deciding to go straight to formula. To dry up I bound my chest, ice packs, peppermint, Tylenol, and Sudafed. The majority of the pain and engorgement was gone in 3 days. And at first I felt sooo much guilt, but now I have a perfectly healthy baby girl that is exceeding her milestones and goals so screw anyone who says breastmilk is the only way to go!
